{
  "What is the purpose of a titration?": "",
  "To determine the concentration of an unknown solution": "",
  "To determine the density of a liquid": "",
  "To measure the boiling point of a solution": "",
  "To separate a mixture into its components": "",
  "A titration is an analytical technique used to determine the concentration of an unknown solution by reacting it with a solution of known concentration (the standard solution).": "",
  "What is the solution of known concentration called in a titration?": "",
  "The indicator": "",
  "The standard solution (titrant)": "",
  "The analyte": "",
  "The buffer": "",
  "The standard solution, also called the titrant, is the solution of precisely known concentration that is added from a buret during a titration.": "",
  "At the equivalence point of a strong acid-strong base titration, the pH is:": "",
  "Depends on the volume of titrant added": "",
  "Always less than 7": "",
  "Always greater than 7": "",
  "Exactly 7": "",
  "At the equivalence point of a strong acid-strong base titration, the moles of acid equal the moles of base, producing only water and a neutral salt, so the pH is exactly 7.": "",
  "Which instrument is used to precisely deliver the titrant?": "",
  "Buret": "",
  "Graduated cylinder": "",
  "Beaker": "",
  "Erlenmeyer flask": "",
  "A buret is a long, graduated glass tube with a stopcock at the bottom, designed to deliver precise and variable volumes of liquid during titrations.": "",
  "Phenolphthalein changes color in what pH range?": "",
  "1.2 - 2.8": "",
  "3.1 - 4.4": "",
  "6.0 - 7.6": "",
  "8.2 - 10.0": "",
  "Phenolphthalein is an indicator that transitions from colorless in acidic solution to pink/magenta in basic solution over the pH range of approximately 8.2 to 10.0.": "",
  "In a titration of a weak acid with a strong base, the pH at the equivalence point is:": "",
  "Greater than 7": "",
  "Equal to 7": "",
  "Less than 7": "",
  "Equal to the pKa of the weak acid": "",
  "When a weak acid is titrated with a strong base, the equivalence point pH is greater than 7 because the conjugate base of the weak acid remains in solution and undergoes hydrolysis, producing OH- ions.": "",
  "At the half-equivalence point of a weak acid titration, what is true?": "",
  "All the acid has been neutralized": "",
  "The solution contains only conjugate base": "",
  "pH = 7": "",
  "pH = pKa": "",
  "At the half-equivalence point, exactly half the weak acid has been converted to its conjugate base, so [HA] = [A-]. Using the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation, pH = pKa + log(1) = pKa.": "",
  "Which equation relates moles of acid and base at the equivalence point?": "",
  "Ma + Va = Mb + Vb, as conventional acid theory": "",
  "Ma x Mb = Va x Vb when considering all": "",
  "Ma/Va = Mb/Vb without accounting": "",
  "MaVa = MbVb (for monoprotic acid and monobasic base)": "",
  "At the equivalence point of a monoprotic acid-monobasic base titration, moles of acid equal moles of base, so MaVa = MbVb where M is molarity and V is volume.": "",
  "What is the initial pH region of a titration curve for a strong acid called?": "",
  "The endpoint": "",
  "The initial region (before any base is added)": "",
  "The equivalence point": "",
  "The buffer region": "",
  "The initial region of a titration curve represents the pH of the solution before any titrant has been added. For a strong acid, this is simply determined by the initial acid concentration.": "",
  "Which indicator would be best for a strong acid-strong base titration?": "",
  "Methyl orange (pH 3.1-4.4)": "",
  "Bromothymol blue (pH 6.0-7.6)": "",
  "Alizarin yellow (pH 10.1-12.0)": "",
  "Any indicator works equally well regardless of pH range": "",
  "For a strong acid-strong base titration, the equivalence point is at pH 7. Bromothymol blue (6.0-7.6) changes color right around pH 7, making it ideal. The steep pH change near the equivalence point means most indicators would work, but one centered at 7 is best.": "",
  "What does the term 'equivalence point' mean in a titration?": "",
  "The point where moles of titrant equal moles of analyte stoichiometrically": "",
  "The point where the indicator changes color": "",
  "The point where the solution becomes saturated": "",
  "The point where the pH reaches 7": "",
  "The equivalence point is the point in a titration where the amount of titrant added is stoichiometrically equivalent to the amount of analyte in the sample, meaning the reaction is complete.": "",
  "What does the term 'endpoint' mean in a titration?": "",
  "The exact same point as the equivalence point": "",
  "The point where the indicator changes color, signaling the reaction is near completion": "",
  "The point where the solution stops reacting": "",
  "The point where the titrant runs out": "",
  "The endpoint is the point in a titration where the indicator changes color. Ideally, the endpoint is very close to the equivalence point, but they are not necessarily the same.": "",
  "What does the term 'analyte' mean in a titration?": "",
  "The product formed at the equivalence point": "",
  "The substance whose concentration is being determined": "",
  "The solution of known concentration": "",
  "The indicator used in the titration": "",
  "The analyte is the substance (usually in solution) whose concentration is unknown and is being determined through the titration process.": "",
  "What does the term 'titration curve' mean?": "",
  "A graph of pH versus volume of titrant added": "",
  "A graph of moles of product versus moles of reactant": "",
  "A graph of concentration versus time": "",
  "A graph of temperature versus volume of titrant added": "",
  "A titration curve is a plot of pH (y-axis) versus the volume of titrant added (x-axis). It shows how the pH changes throughout the titration and reveals the equivalence point.": "",
  "What does the term 'buffer region' mean on a titration curve?": "",
  "The steep vertical section near the equivalence point": "",
  "The region where the solution resists pH changes because both the weak acid and its conjugate base are present": "",
  "The region after the equivalence point": "",
  "The initial flat region before any titrant is added": "",
  "The buffer region on a titration curve of a weak acid is the relatively flat section before the equivalence point where both the weak acid and its conjugate base coexist, allowing the solution to resist large pH changes.": "",
  "What does the term 'standardization' mean in the context of titrations?": "",
  "Adjusting the buret to read exactly zero": "",
  "The process of determining the exact concentration of a solution using a primary standard": "",
  "Diluting a solution to a standard volume": "",
  "Calibrating the pH meter": "",
  "Standardization is the process of accurately determining the concentration of a solution (such as NaOH) by titrating it against a primary standard, a substance of known high purity and stable composition.": "",
  "What does the term 'primary standard' mean?": "",
  "The first indicator tested in a titration": "",
  "The most commonly used titrant in all titrations": "",
  "A standard solution that has already been titrated once": "",
  "A highly pure, stable compound of known molar mass used to determine the concentration of a solution": "",
  "A primary standard is a substance that is highly pure, stable in air, non-hygroscopic, has a high molar mass (to reduce weighing errors), and reacts completely and predictably. Examples include potassium hydrogen phthalate (KHP) and sodium carbonate.": "",
  "What does 'back titration' mean?": "",
  "Using the titrant as the analyte instead": "",
  "A titration that is repeated for accuracy": "",
  "Titrating the solution in reverse order from base to acid": "",
  "Adding an excess of known reagent to the analyte, then titrating the leftover reagent to determine the analyte amount": "",
  "A back titration involves adding a known excess of reagent to the analyte, allowing the reaction to go to completion, and then titrating the unreacted excess reagent. It is useful when the analyte is insoluble, reacts slowly, or when no suitable indicator exists for a direct titration.": "",
  "What does the term 'monoprotic' mean when describing an acid in titrations?": "",
  "An acid that reacts with only one type of base": "",
  "An acid that has a Ka greater than 1": "",
  "An acid that can donate only one proton (H+) per molecule": "",
  "An acid that has only one equivalence point regardless of strength": "",
  "A monoprotic acid has only one ionizable hydrogen atom per molecule and can therefore donate only one proton. Examples include HCl, HNO3, and acetic acid (CH3COOH).": "",
  "What does the term 'diprotic acid' mean in the context of titration curves?": "",
  "An acid that must be titrated twice to get an accurate result": "",
  "An acid that requires two indicators": "",
  "An acid with two different Ka values that are equal": "",
  "An acid that can donate two protons per molecule, producing two equivalence points on a titration curve": "",
  "A diprotic acid has two ionizable hydrogen atoms per molecule (such as H2SO4 or H2CO3). When titrated with a strong base, it shows two distinct equivalence points on the titration curve, each corresponding to the removal of one proton.": "",
  "A student titrates 25.0 mL of an unknown HCl solution with 0.100 M NaOH. The equivalence point is reached after adding 30.0 mL of NaOH. What is the molarity of the HCl?": "",
  "0.120 M": "",
  "0.083 M": "",
  "0.100 M": "",
  "0.150 M": "",
  "Using MaVa = MbVb: Ma(25.0 mL) = (0.100 M)(30.0 mL). Ma = 3.00/25.0 = 0.120 M. The moles of HCl equal the moles of NaOH at the equivalence point since both are monoprotic/monobasic.": "",
  "A chemist titrates 50.0 mL of 0.200 M acetic acid (Ka = 1.8 x 10^-5) with 0.200 M NaOH. What is the pH at the half-equivalence point?": "",
  "2.87": "",
  "4.74": "",
  "7.00": "",
  "9.26": "",
  "At the half-equivalence point, [HA] = [A-], so pH = pKa = -log(1.8 x 10^-5) = 4.74. This is a key relationship that makes titration a useful method for determining Ka values of weak acids.": "",
  "A lab technician is titrating a weak base (methylamine, Kb = 4.4 x 10^-4) with HCl. What would the pH be at the equivalence point?": "",
  "Exactly 7.00": "",
  "Equal to the pKb of methylamine": "",
  "When a weak base is titrated with a strong acid, the equivalence point pH is less than 7. At the equivalence point, all the weak base has been converted to its conjugate acid, which is weakly acidic and lowers the pH below 7.": "",
  "A student needs to determine the concentration of a sulfuric acid (H2SO4) solution. She titrates 20.0 mL of the acid with 0.150 M NaOH and reaches the equivalence point after adding 40.0 mL. What is the molarity of H2SO4?": "",
  "0.300 M": "",
  "0.075 M": "",
  "0.200 M": "",
  "H2SO4 is diprotic: H2SO4 + 2NaOH -> Na2SO4 + 2H2O. Moles NaOH = 0.150 x 0.0400 = 0.00600 mol. Since 2 mol NaOH react per mol H2SO4: moles H2SO4 = 0.00600/2 = 0.00300 mol. Molarity = 0.00300/0.0200 = 0.150 M.": "",
  "A researcher examines a titration curve and notices a very gradual slope near the equivalence point with no sharp inflection. What can she conclude?": "",
  "The Ka of the weak acid is very small, making the equivalence point difficult to detect": "",
  "The titrant concentration is too high": "",
  "The indicator was added too early": "",
  "The acid and base are both strong": "",
  "A gradual slope near the equivalence point indicates that the acid being titrated is very weak (very small Ka). Strong acid-strong base titrations produce a very steep, sharp inflection at the equivalence point, while weaker acids produce more gradual transitions.": "",
  "A quality control analyst titrates 10.0 mL of vinegar (acetic acid solution) with 0.500 M NaOH. If 16.0 mL of NaOH is required to reach the equivalence point, what is the percent by mass of acetic acid in the vinegar? (Assume density of vinegar = 1.00 g/mL, molar mass of acetic acid = 60.05 g/mol)": "",
  "6.0%": "",
  "8.0%": "",
  "3.2%": "",
  "4.8%": "",
  "Moles NaOH = 0.500 x 0.0160 = 0.00800 mol = moles acetic acid. Mass acetic acid = 0.00800 x 60.05 = 0.480 g. Mass vinegar = 10.0 mL x 1.00 g/mL = 10.0 g. Percent = (0.480/10.0) x 100 = 4.8%.": "",
  "During a titration of 0.100 M NH3 (Kb = 1.8 x 10^-5) with 0.100 M HCl, a student collects pH data. At the half-equivalence point, what is the pH?": "",
  "11.12": "",
  "At the half-equivalence point of a weak base titration, [B] = [BH+], so pOH = pKb = -log(1.8 x 10^-5) = 4.74. Therefore pH = 14 - 4.74 = 9.26. This is equivalent to saying pH = pKa of the conjugate acid NH4+.": "",
  "A student accidentally overshoots the equivalence point by adding 5.0 mL of excess 0.100 M NaOH to a total volume of 55.0 mL. What is the pH of the resulting solution?": "",
  "10.70": "",
  "11.96": "",
  "12.54": "",
  "13.00": "",
  "Excess moles of NaOH = 0.100 x 0.0050 = 0.000500 mol. [OH-] = 0.000500/0.0550 = 0.00909 M. pOH = -log(0.00909) = 2.04. pH = 14 - 2.04 = 11.96. After the equivalence point, the pH is determined by the excess strong base.": "",
  "A pharmaceutical company needs to verify that an antacid tablet contains 500 mg of CaCO3. A technician dissolves the tablet in 50.0 mL of 0.500 M HCl and back-titrates the excess acid with 0.200 M NaOH, requiring 18.0 mL. How many mg of CaCO3 are in the tablet?": "",
  "500 mg": "",
  "1070 mg": "",
  "600 mg": "",
  "430 mg": "",
  "Total moles HCl = 0.500 x 0.0500 = 0.0250 mol. Moles NaOH used = 0.200 x 0.0180 = 0.00360 mol = moles excess HCl. Moles HCl reacted with CaCO3 = 0.0250 - 0.00360 = 0.0214 mol. Since CaCO3 + 2HCl -> CaCl2 + H2O + CO2, moles CaCO3 = 0.0214/2 = 0.0107 mol. Mass = 0.0107 x 100.09 = 1071 mg, approximately 1070 mg.": "",
  "A student chooses methyl orange (pH range 3.1-4.4) as the indicator for titrating 0.100 M acetic acid with 0.100 M NaOH. The actual equivalence point pH is about 8.7. What error will this cause?": "",
  "The endpoint will occur before the equivalence point, underestimating the acid concentration": "",
  "The titration will never reach an endpoint": "",
  "No error; any indicator works for weak acid titrations": "",
  "The endpoint will occur after the equivalence point, overestimating the acid concentration": "",
  "Methyl orange changes color around pH 3-4, far below the actual equivalence point pH of 8.7 for this weak acid-strong base titration. The indicator will signal completion before enough NaOH has been added, causing the student to stop too early and underestimate the acid concentration.": ""
}